PROBLEM STATEMENT
The primary challenge in analyzing permanently shadowed regions (PSRs) on the Moon lies
in the quality of the imaging data. Due to the absence of sunlight, PSRs receive minimal
illumination, leading to images that are dark, noisy, and lack sufficient contrast. These
conditions make it difficult to distinguish surface features or identify critical resources such
as water ice. Chandrayaan-2, while equipped with advanced instruments, faces inherent
limitations in capturing detailed and clear images of these regions, leaving a gap between the
raw data collected and the actionable insights needed for scientific research and exploration.
Additionally, the traditional methods of image processing often fall short in addressing the
unique challenges posed by PSR data. Standard enhancement techniques may inadvertently
amplify noise or fail to bring out subtle features hidden in the shadowed terrains. The absence
of a tailored approach for PSR imaging hinders the ability to extract meaningful information,
which is crucial for understanding lunar geology, identifying resource deposits, and planning
future missions.
